<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="4" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1913,2013]" lastBlockId="3.[151,1437,153,431]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="4" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,1913,1940]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zeller" authorityYear="1848" box="[280,411,1915,1940]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Hypsotropa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[280,411,1915,1940]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Hypsotropa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterized by a basally nearly parallel-sided valva with a much narrower distal half. A distinct spike-like process from ventral base of valva and short triangular process in the distal portion of valva characterize the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ragonot" authorityYear="1888" box="[285,425,1986,2012]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Hypsotropa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="unipunctella">
<emphasis box="[285,425,1986,2012]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">unipunctella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-group. In the female genitalia, the emargination on the posterior margin of sternum VIII is shallow, the colliculum is usually distinct and the corpus bursae is large, without a signum. Externally 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zeller" authorityYear="1848" box="[1305,1436,154,179]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Hypsotropa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1305,1436,154,179]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Hypsotropa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species are rather broad-winged 
<taxonomicName box="[519,643,189,215]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Phycitinae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Anerastiini">Anerastiini</taxonomicName>
which can be confused with some 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zeller" authorityYear="1867" box="[1046,1183,189,215]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Ematheudes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1046,1183,189,215]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Ematheudes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species, but the labial palpus are obliquely upturned far beyond the vertex of the head (
<bibRefCitation author="Hampson, G. F." box="[879,1096,225,252]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" pagination="55 - 131" refId="ref15316" refString="Hampson, G. F. (1918) A classification of the Pyralidae, subfamily Hypsotropinae. Proceedings of the General Meetings for Scientific Business of the Zoological Society of London, 1918, 55 - 131. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.1918. tb 02077. x" type="journal article" year="1918">Hampson 1918: 67</bibRefCitation>
) (
<figureCitation box="[1119,1191,225,251]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1945,1970]" captionTargetBox="[203,1385,179,1918]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[203,1385,179,1918]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Hypsotropa unipunctella. 1, 2. Adults. 3. Head. 4, 5. Male genitalia. 4a, 5a. Cornuti (enlarged). b. Ventral view. 6. Female genitalia. 1, 5. ♂, Crimea. Prep. no. 221/18. 2. ♂, Zaporizhzhia reg. 3. ♀, Crimea. 4. ♂, Zabaikalskiy kray. Prep. no. 260/18. 6. ♀, Crimea. Prep. no. 224/18." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3602157" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3602157/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Figs 3</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1204,1232,225,251]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–10" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1870,1895]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1824]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1435,181,1844]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 7–10. Hypsotropa limbella. 7, 8. Adults. a. Head. 9. Female genitalia. 10. Male genitalia. 7, 10. ♂, Crete. Prep. no. 283/18. 8, 9. ♀, Dalmatia. Prep. no. 282/18." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3602159" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3602159/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">7a</figureCitation>
) whereas those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zeller" authorityYear="1867" box="[151,288,261,287]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Ematheudes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,288,261,287]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Ematheudes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are downcurved (
<figureCitation box="[490,573,261,287]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–14" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1945,1970]" captionTargetBox="[203,1385,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[203,1385,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 11–14. Ematheudes punctellus. 11. Adult. 12. Head. 13. Male genitalia. 14. Female genitalia. 11, 12. ♀, Crimea. 13. ♂, Crimea. Prep. no. 225/18. 14. ♀, Crimea. Prep. no. 47/19." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3602161" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3602161/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,153,431]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,296,323]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Distribution.</emphasis>
The great majority of species (21) is recorded from the Afrotropical region (
<bibRefCitation author="Hampson, G. F." box="[1216,1391,297,323]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" pagination="55 - 131" refId="ref15316" refString="Hampson, G. F. (1918) A classification of the Pyralidae, subfamily Hypsotropinae. Proceedings of the General Meetings for Scientific Business of the Zoological Society of London, 1918, 55 - 131. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.1918. tb 02077. x" type="journal article" year="1918">Hampson 1918</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="De Prins, J. &amp; De Prins, W." pageId="3" pageNumber="4" refId="ref14508" refString="De Prins, J. &amp; De Prins, W. (2019) Afromoths, online database of Afrotropical moth species (Lepidoptera). World Wide Web electronic publication. Available from: http: // www. afromoths. net (accessed 19 October 2019)" type="url" year="2019">De Prins &amp; De Prins 2019</bibRefCitation>
). The Palaearctic species are most diverse in the Mediterranean area (
<bibRefCitation author="Leraut, P." box="[1202,1345,333,359]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" refId="ref16023" refString="Leraut, P. (2014) Moths of Europe. Vol. 4. Pyralids 2. NAP Editions, Paris, 440 pp." type="book" year="2014">Leraut 2014</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Gaston, F. J. &amp; Macia, R. &amp; Ylla, J. &amp; Huertas-Dionisio, M." pageId="3" pageNumber="4" pagination="75 - 88" refId="ref14646" refString="Gaston, F. J., Macia, R., Ylla, J. &amp; Huertas-Dionisio, M. (2016) El Genero Hypsotropa Zeller, 1848 en la Peninsula Iberica, con la descripcion de una especie nueva (Lepidoptera: Pyralidae, Phycitinae, Peoriini). Boletin de la Sociedad Entomologica Aragonesa (S. E. A.), 58, 75 - 88." type="journal article" year="2016">
Gastón 
<emphasis box="[151,200,369,395]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">et al</emphasis>
. 2016
</bibRefCitation>
). Several species are known from Oriental, Australian and Neotropical regions (
<bibRefCitation author="Nuss, M. &amp; Landry, B. &amp; Mally, R. &amp; Vegliante, F. &amp; Trankner, A. &amp; Bauer, F. &amp; Hayden, J. &amp; Segerer, A. &amp; Schouten, R. &amp; Li, H. &amp; Trofimova, T. &amp; Solis, M. A. &amp; De Prins, J. &amp; Speidel, W." box="[1167,1352,369,395]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" refId="ref16145" refString="Nuss, M., Landry, B., Mally, R., Vegliante, F., Trankner, A., Bauer, F., Hayden, J., Segerer, A., Schouten, R., Li, H., Trofimova, T., Solis, M. A., De Prins, J. &amp; Speidel, W. (2003 - 2019) Global Information System on Pyraloidea. Available from: http: // www. pyraloidea. org (accessed 19 October 2019)" type="url" year="2003">
Nuss 
<emphasis box="[1231,1280,369,395]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">et al</emphasis>
. 
<date box="[1294,1352,369,395]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="2003" valueMax="2019">2003</date>
</bibRefCitation>
–2019). One species is reported from 
<collectingCountry box="[480,574,405,431]" name="Ukraine" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Ukraine</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
